I've been to Kyma plenty of times now and each experience has been quite different. My last visit was quite disappointing service-wise, our server Kylene just kind of forgot about us. We had to ask for bread where it is usually brought to the table without asking, our drinks took forever, and it took her a while to take our order. She said she had a big table that kept her busy. Really?? What kind of an excuse is this? If you are in the weeds, don't take an additional table. Why would I care about her other tables. If I go out, I expect excellent service no matter what.

That said, the food here is good, if a bit too heavy on the oil. But that's Greek, I get it.
They have two different food menus, one for the dining room, one for the bar. I'd recommend asking for both as there is a difference in price but not the size (which is strange). The waitress first said that the bar menu offers smaller portions but then when our items were brought to the table, she said the portions are actually the same.

Here are some of the menu items I've tried here through my visits. 

Apps: 
- "Kyma's Been off the Menu for Years, Non-Stop-Ordered" Baby Back Pork Ribs - excellent. Fall-off-the bone tender deliciousness;
- Truffled Veal Sweetbread Nuggets "Professionally Cooked the Way They Should Be" - these were a-ok, we ordered sauce on the side and with quinoa salad (the salad was too citrus-y for my taste);
- Calamari pasta - this dish had a strange consistency and texture, not my favorite;
- Braised lamb cheeks - good but not as tender as ribs and quite fatty;
- grilled octopus - some of the best in Atlanta.

Dishes:
- Giant prawns  - perfectly cooked and very juicy;
- Lamb 3 ways - I expected it to be more tender and juicy.

They have a very well stocked bar and a small patio although the outside tables are tiny if you plan on eating al fresco.

Overall: if you like greek food, you will like this place.
